### ScanResult Response Object

Source: https://context7.com/dariyd/react-native-document-scanner/llms.txt

The ScanResult object is returned by `launchScanner` and contains the status of the scan and image data. It includes properties for cancellation, errors, error messages, and an array of scanned images.

```APIDOC
## ScanResult Response Object

### Description
The result object returned by `launchScanner` containing scan status and image data.

### Interface
```typescript
interface ScanResult {
  didCancel?: boolean;      // true if user cancelled
  error?: boolean;          // true if error occurred
  errorMessage?: string;    // error description (debug only)
  images?: ImageObject[];   // array of scanned images
}
```

### Usage Examples

#### Handling all response cases
```javascript
// Example: Handling all response cases
const result = await launchScanner();

if (result.didCancel) {
  console.log('User pressed cancel button');
  // No images property will be present
}

if (result.error) {
  console.log('Error details:', result.errorMessage);
  // Common errors:
  // - "Activity doesn't exist" (Android)
  // - "Camera permission denied" (iOS)
  // - "ML Kit not available" (Android - missing Google Play Services)
}

if (result.images) {
  console.log(`Successfully scanned ${result.images.length} pages`);
  // images array contains 1-10 pages (based on scanner configuration)
}
```

### Response Object Fields

- **didCancel** (boolean) - Optional - `true` if the user cancelled the scan operation.
- **error** (boolean) - Optional - `true` if an error occurred during the scan.
- **errorMessage** (string) - Optional - A description of the error that occurred (primarily for debugging).
- **images** (Array<ImageObject>) - Optional - An array of `ImageObject` containing the scanned images.
```

### ImageObject Metadata

Source: https://context7.com/dariyd/react-native-document-scanner/llms.txt

Each scanned page is represented by an `ImageObject`, which provides comprehensive metadata and the processed image. This object includes the `uri` of the cached image file, its `fileName` (a UUID), `type` (MIME type like `image/jpeg` or `image/png`), `width` and `height` in pixels, `fileSize` in bytes, and an optional `base64` string representation of the image.
